Project: QuickKlinik

General Principles:
- Use strict TypeScript.
- Use server components by default.
- All business logic must run server-side.
- Never trust client-side validation.
- Every state-changing action must create an audit log entry.
- No hardcoded mock data beyond development seed files.
- All configuration must come from environment variables.
- Use a layered architecture: UI → Service Layer → Data Layer.
- Follow modular folder structure by domain.
- Use Supabase for database, auth, and optional realtime/storage.

Architecture Rules:
- App Router structure.
- Use server actions where appropriate.
- API routes only when external consumption is required.
- Centralized authentication middleware (Supabase Auth).
- Role-based authorization guard at route level and action level.
- Soft deletes for all critical records.
- Use transactions for financial and inventory operations.

Database Rules:
- Supabase (PostgreSQL). Use Supabase client/server helpers; no separate ORM unless justified.
- Schema via Supabase migrations (SQL in repo).
- All tables must include:
  - id (uuid, default gen_random_uuid())
  - createdAt (timestamptz)
  - updatedAt (timestamptz)
  - deletedAt (nullable timestamptz)
- All tenant-scoped tables must include clinicId (or organizationId) and enforce RLS.
- Index queue-related fields and clinicId/organizationId for tenant queries.
- Never cascade delete financial or audit records.

Whitelabel / Multi-Tenant Rules:
- Treat each clinic/hospital as a tenant. Isolate data by clinicId (or organizationId) everywhere.
- No hardcoded clinic name, logo, or primary color in UI. Source from tenant config (DB or env).
- Tenant config: displayName, logoUrl, primaryColor, supportEmail, (optional) customDomain. Store in clinics/organizations table or tenant_settings.
- Use Supabase RLS so all queries are automatically scoped to the current tenant (set via set_config('app.current_clinic_id', ...) in middleware or server context).
- Single codebase; tenant chosen by domain, subdomain, or login context. No forking per client.

Security Rules:
- Enforce RBAC strictly (Supabase Auth roles + app-level role checks).
- Use Supabase RLS for row-level tenant isolation.
- Validate all inputs using schema validation.
- Rate-limit public endpoints.
- Log failed authentication attempts.
- Do not expose internal IDs publicly (use UUIDs and avoid sequential IDs in URLs).
- Payment flow must use provider redirect or secure confirmation.

UI Rules:
- Mobile-first responsive layout.
- Accessible (WCAG friendly).
- Kiosk mode must disable browser navigation and external links.
- Loading states required for all async actions.
- No UI library until layout baseline is approved.

Design System / Theme Tokens:
- Use semantic theme tokens (Tailwind + CSS variables) for ALL colors: `bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `bg-card`, `text-muted-foreground`, `bg-primary`, `ring-ring`, etc.
- Never hardcode hex colors in components. If a new color is needed, add it as a CSS variable token in `app/globals.css`.
- Brand defaults in `app/globals.css`: `--brand-bg`, `--brand-fg`, `--brand-primary`, `--brand-accent`, `--brand-tint`, `--brand-border`, `--brand-muted`, `--brand-muted-fg`, `--brand-danger`. Use semantic tokens (`--primary`, `--accent`, etc.) in UI, not the brand hex variables directly.
- Extended shade families (optional): `--color-baltic-blue-{50..950}`, `--color-teal-*`, `--color-verdigris-*`, `--color-mint-leaf-*`, `--color-cream-*`.
- Tenant branding overrides must flow through CSS variables (HSL triplets):
  - `--tenant-primary`, `--tenant-primary-foreground`, `--tenant-accent`, `--tenant-ring`
  - These are mapped to `--primary`, `--primary-foreground`, `--accent`, `--ring` in `app/globals.css`

Domain Modules:
- Auth
- Clinics
- Doctors
- Patients
- Appointments
- Queue
- OTC Products
- Inventory
- Orders
- Payments
- Audit Logs

Testing:
- Write basic integration tests for:
  - Appointment booking
  - OTC order creation
  - Inventory deduction
  - Role enforcement

Documentation:
- Every module must include README explaining purpose and data flow.